723835292.jpg)  \nFigure   1.   a) Device configuration of all-inorganic PVSCs. b) Chemical structures and DFT  calculation results of TPE-S. c) Energy band alignment for each layer in   $\\mathsf{C s P b I}_{2}\\mathsf{B r}$   inorganic  solar cells.  \n\ni) the improvement of the crystal lin it y of the perovskite film  deposited on the TPE-S layer, which suppresses undesired  charge carrier recombination s; ii) TPE-S exhibits high transparency in visible region and chemical PH neutrality, which is  beneficial for long-term stability.  \n\npoly(3-hex yl thi oph ene), poly(3,4-ethylene di oxy thi oph ene):poly­ (styrene s ulf on ate) (PEDOT:PSS),  which could cause proces s ability difficulties and batch-to-batch variations.  In contrast, dopant-free organic small-molecular HTMs could achieve  highly efficient PVSCs and have much better process ability,  reproducibility, higher transmittance in the visible region, tunable energy levels, and improved long-term stability.  \n\nThe TPE-S molecule was synthesized via a Buchwald– Hartwig  reaction  between  1,1,2,2-tetrakis(4-b romo phenyl) ethane and bis(4-(methylthio)phenyl)amine. The synthetic  details with characterization data are provided in the Supporting Information. Density functional theory (DFT) calculations were carried out to investigate the molecular geometry at  the   $\\mathrm{B3LYP/6{\\cdot}31+}$   (d, p) level. As shown in Figure 1b, the opti- mized geometry of TPE-S is highly twisty that is beneficial for  weakening intermolecular interactions. Furthermore, in its electrostatic potential surface (EPS) image, more negative charges  are distributed at the S atoms of TPE-S, which can serve as the  Lewis base anchors to passivate perovskite defects.  \n\nIn this work, we design and synthesize a new small-mole­ cular HTM, namely, TPE-S, based on a tetra phenyl ethylene  (TPE) ( Figure   1 b). Compared to other previously reported TPEbased HTMs,  we introduce sulfur (S) atoms to replace the  conventionally used oxygen (O) atoms on the TPE molecule  based on the consideration that S atoms can passivate defects  in perovskite more efficiently by coordinating   $\\mathrm{Pb}^{2+}$   vacancies.  When utilized as the dopant-free HTM in inverted all-inorganic   $\\mathrm{Cs}\\mathrm{Pb}{\\I}_{2}\\mathrm{Br}$   PVSCs, the chl oro benzene solution containing TPE-S  is processed directly onto the indium tin oxide (ITO) substrates  at room temperature without any post-treatment. The as-optimized all-inorganic device realized a champion PCE value of \n\n  $15.4\\%$   with a remarkable stabilized power output (SPO) of \n\n  ${\\approx}14.3\\%$   within   $650~\\mathrm{s}$  .\nOutput:"}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "## Output\n\n(ORGANIZATION<|>NONE<|>INFORMATION DISCOVERY<|>TRUE<|>NONE<|>NONE<|>The organization involved in the research is not specified in the text, but it is implied that the research was conducted by a group of scientists from various institutions.<|>Kui Jiang, Jing Wang, Fei Wu, Qifan Xue,\\* Qin Yao, Jianquan Zhang, Yihuang Chen,  Guangye Zhang, Zonglong Zhu, He Yan, Linna Zhu,\\* and Hin-Lap Yip\\*  \nstability of perovskite materials under  photo-, thermal, or moisture stresses, and  the volatile nature of the organic cations in  the prototype (organic–inorganic hybrid)  perovskite composition, may hinder their  commercialization.  To address the stability issues, all-inorganic perovskite solar  cells (PVSCs) based on cesium (Cs) lead  halide has been developed and has drawn  considerable research attention, wherein  the organic cations in the perovskite structure are completely replaced by the inorganic Cs ions, whose atomic size is suitable  to form the perovskite crystal structure.   Among all the Cs-based PVSCs, the  cesium lead iodine   $(\\mathrm{Cs}\\mathrm{PbI}_{3})$  ) has the most  favorable bandgap   $(1.73\\ \\mathrm{eV})$  , but the black  phase of   $\\mathrm{Cs}\\mathrm{PbI}_{3}$   is not stable at room tem- perature.  Therefore, various m